BEN FRENKEL: Welcome
to this session

00:00:01.640 --> 00:00:05.440
on developing successful
games with Google Play.

00:00:05.440 --> 00:00:09.440
Hope you're all having a
fantastic I/O. Is that true?

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:10.830
You guys having a fun time here?

00:00:10.830 --> 00:00:11.670
[CHEERS]

00:00:11.670 --> 00:00:12.660
Whoo!

00:00:12.660 --> 00:00:13.167
Exactly.

00:00:13.167 --> 00:00:14.000
Let's get energized.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:15.583
I know it's 10 o'clock
in the morning,

00:00:15.583 --> 00:00:18.820
but let's get excited
for game stuff, right?

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:22.131
Did you guys enjoy all the
festivities last night?

00:00:22.131 --> 00:00:22.630
Yes?

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:24.080
I'm seeing some nodding heads.

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:26.246
Did you guys like the
blankets they were handing out

00:00:26.246 --> 00:00:27.670
because it was freezing?

00:00:27.670 --> 00:00:29.280
I certainly did.

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:30.400
I grabbed one of those.

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:31.700
So I'm Ben Frenkel.

00:00:31.700 --> 00:00:33.620
I'm a product manager
on the Play Games team.

00:00:33.620 --> 00:00:36.140
And in this session,
I'm going to provide you

00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:40.520
an overview of what Play Games
is doing for game developers.

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:44.110
And I'm joined today by
my esteemed colleague, TI,

00:00:44.110 --> 00:00:47.620
who's going to go into the
nitty-gritty details of how

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:51.290
to implement both Play Games
and other Play services.

00:00:51.290 --> 00:00:56.000
And we also have a very
special guest with us today,

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.810
Duke Kim from
Netmarble, who's going

00:00:58.810 --> 00:01:02.056
to talk about both a
background for Netmarble,

00:01:02.056 --> 00:01:03.930
what games they have,
as well as what they're

00:01:03.930 --> 00:01:07.060
doing with Play Games
and Play overall

00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:09.430
to improve their business.

00:01:09.430 --> 00:01:12.760
But first, let's see
a quick show of hands.

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:16.470
How many of you in this
room are game developers

00:01:16.470 --> 00:01:19.680
or involved in
the game industry?

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:20.380
Excellent.

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:21.860
That is virtually everybody.

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:24.930
I do see a few familiar
faces from the session

00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:26.210
I did earlier in the week.

00:01:26.210 --> 00:01:29.410
How many of you were
at that session?

00:01:29.410 --> 00:01:30.060
Good amount.

00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:30.560
All right.

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:32.059
Well, the good news
for you, I'm not

00:01:32.059 --> 00:01:33.810
going to bore you with
the same material.

00:01:33.810 --> 00:01:37.170
There is fresh content
here, and plenty of it.

00:01:37.170 --> 00:01:40.260
But for those of you
who were not there,

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:43.050
I'll go and provide some
background on what Play Games

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:44.180
Services is all about.

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:47.140
So our mission is to
provide developers

00:01:47.140 --> 00:01:53.340
the tools and services they
need to create great games,

00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:55.790
and make money while
they're doing it, too.

00:01:55.790 --> 00:02:00.380
And in 2013, at I/O, we
launched Play Games Services

00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:01.630
for the first time.

00:02:01.630 --> 00:02:04.100
And when we launched,
we had the basics.

00:02:04.100 --> 00:02:06.270
We had achievements,
we had leaderboards,

00:02:06.270 --> 00:02:10.340
we had a multiplayer stack,
and so on and so forth.

00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:13.970
And since then, we've become
the fastest-growing game network

00:02:13.970 --> 00:02:14.950
ever.

00:02:14.950 --> 00:02:18.700
Fast forward to
today, and each month,

00:02:18.700 --> 00:02:22.280
hundreds of millions of people
sign into Play Games Services,

00:02:22.280 --> 00:02:26.860
and 50% of the top 500
games are integrated.

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:28.910
But over the years,
the needs of developers

00:02:28.910 --> 00:02:30.640
have evolved
substantially, and we've

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:33.530
had to evolve along with them.

00:02:33.530 --> 00:02:35.540
And so, Play Games
Services has since

00:02:35.540 --> 00:02:38.600
expanded to offer things
like video recording

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:40.880
and predictive
analytics, and tools

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:42.220
to support live operations.

00:02:45.010 --> 00:02:46.790
And another way
we've had to evolve

00:02:46.790 --> 00:02:49.270
is, we needed to start
bringing our tools

00:02:49.270 --> 00:02:54.450
to the different products
that our partners use.

00:02:54.450 --> 00:02:56.530
And in particular,
what we observed

00:02:56.530 --> 00:03:00.470
after a number of conversations
with large developers

00:03:00.470 --> 00:03:03.180
and small developers, that
game developers typically

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:05.390
fell into one of two camps.

00:03:05.390 --> 00:03:09.850
They either had their own game
engine that was built in C++,

00:03:09.850 --> 00:03:14.310
or they used a game
engine, oftentimes a Unity

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:15.300
or a Cocos2d.

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:18.310
So just a quick show of hands,
how many of you have your own

00:03:18.310 --> 00:03:23.362
game engine that you've
built in C++ specifically?

00:03:23.362 --> 00:03:25.570
How many of you have something,
your own game engine,

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:28.070
not built in C++,
but another language?

00:03:28.070 --> 00:03:28.890
Didn't think so.

00:03:28.890 --> 00:03:29.390
All right.

00:03:29.390 --> 00:03:31.160
That is not a real
thing, it turns out.

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:34.630
And then, how many use a
game engine of some sort?

00:03:34.630 --> 00:03:37.430
OK, that's the vast
majority of the audience.

00:03:37.430 --> 00:03:40.610
And that makes
sense, which is why,

00:03:40.610 --> 00:03:43.400
when we looked at what
our partners were doing,

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:46.610
we realized we absolutely had to
have support for game engines.

00:03:46.610 --> 00:03:49.120
So we actually
have a Unity plugin

00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:54.234
that is a open-source project
that we maintain on GitHub,

00:03:54.234 --> 00:03:56.650
and you can go check it out
and make use of those services

00:03:56.650 --> 00:03:57.700
immediately.

00:03:57.700 --> 00:04:00.130
In addition to that, we
also, a couple of years ago,

00:04:00.130 --> 00:04:05.550
launched our C++ SDK, so that,
for those of you who do not

00:04:05.550 --> 00:04:10.400
greatly enjoy crossing the JNI
bridge into Java land for doing

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:13.620
all of your integrations, you
can do them directly in C++

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:14.410
instead.

00:04:14.410 --> 00:04:17.600
And it just so happens
that, if you have a C++ SDK,

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:20.560
it's relatively easy to
integrate Play Games Services

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:25.710
into game engines that
are built also on C++.

00:04:25.710 --> 00:04:27.950
And Cocos2d is just
such a game engine,

00:04:27.950 --> 00:04:30.960
and they have native support
for a number of different Play

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:34.240
Games Services features to
make it very easy to integrate.

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:37.370
And we're working with
partners to deepen and simplify

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:39.570
integrations all the
time, and we're always

00:04:39.570 --> 00:04:41.970
on the lookout for
new and exciting game

00:04:41.970 --> 00:04:44.790
engines to partner with.

00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:49.690
One recent entry in the
game engine fray is Defold.

00:04:49.690 --> 00:04:51.940
I don't know how many of you
are familiar with Defold,

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:54.530
but Defold is a
lightweight game engine

00:04:54.530 --> 00:04:58.800
from our friends
at King, and it's

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:03.100
a tool that makes it very,
very easy to make games.

00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:05.700
It's a simplified
developer experience,

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:08.480
so developers can focus on
the fun and engaging part

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:09.410
of the game.

00:05:09.410 --> 00:05:10.970
And a few months
ago, they gave me

00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:13.080
a sneak preview of
their integration

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:16.350
with Play Games Services,
and I was blown away

00:05:16.350 --> 00:05:17.400
at how simple it was.

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:20.580
I had to do a double take,
because the integration looked

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:21.980
so easy.

00:05:21.980 --> 00:05:24.420
And this is how
it works for them.

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:27.870
So you first have to go into
the Play Developer Console

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:28.950
and grab an ID.

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:31.230
This is a very easy thing to do.

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:33.690
And then you go into
the Defold management

00:05:33.690 --> 00:05:36.410
console and copy and paste
it in there somewhere.

00:05:36.410 --> 00:05:40.020
And then, once you've done
that very small bit of work,

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:42.760
you can then, in a
single line of code,

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:46.370
integrate Sign-In with
Play Games Services.

00:05:46.370 --> 00:05:48.210
So it's almost instantaneous.

00:05:48.210 --> 00:05:50.610
And when they
showed it to me, it

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:54.780
was something that I believe all
game engines should ultimately

00:05:54.780 --> 00:05:56.590
aspire to be able to accomplish.

00:05:56.590 --> 00:05:58.960
It should take less than
an hour to integrate,

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:02.962
and they really bring
that vision to fruition.

00:06:02.962 --> 00:06:05.170
And we're excited to see
them launch their Play Games

00:06:05.170 --> 00:06:08.880
Services support
later this year.

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:11.010
So there's a lot of other
territory we could cover,

00:06:11.010 --> 00:06:12.910
but I'm going to
focus on three things

00:06:12.910 --> 00:06:15.500
that Play Games can do to
help you engage and retain

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:16.600
your players.

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:19.230
So first, we're going to talk
about how the Play Games Video

00:06:19.230 --> 00:06:21.750
Recording API can help
you harness the energy

00:06:21.750 --> 00:06:24.570
and enthusiasm of
your gaming community

00:06:24.570 --> 00:06:26.590
to deepen player engagement.

00:06:26.590 --> 00:06:29.680
Then, we'll cover how you
can make dynamic updates

00:06:29.680 --> 00:06:33.710
with services that Play Games
Services provides, and finally,

00:06:33.710 --> 00:06:36.530
talk about how you can use our
predictive analytics to tune

00:06:36.530 --> 00:06:40.860
and tailor your game to
different player segments.

00:06:40.860 --> 00:06:43.170
So let's kick
things off with how

00:06:43.170 --> 00:06:47.250
we can help you deepen your
engagement with your player

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:49.189
community.

00:06:49.189 --> 00:06:50.980
So for a bit of
background, late last year,

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:55.260
we made it possible for players
to record their gameplay

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:58.240
from the Play Games app.

00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:00.830
And in the next few weeks, we'll
be making the Video Recording

00:07:00.830 --> 00:07:04.730
API available to all
developers, so that players

00:07:04.730 --> 00:07:08.720
will be able to invoke that same
recording experience directly

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:10.087
from your games.

00:07:10.087 --> 00:07:12.670
And Duke is going to talk about
how they're doing that in some

00:07:12.670 --> 00:07:14.730
of Netmarble titles later on.

00:07:14.730 --> 00:07:16.570
Players will also
have the option

00:07:16.570 --> 00:07:19.980
to live stream their
gameplay to YouTube, as well.

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:22.040
It's a really powerful feature.

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:24.650
And we've seen a
lot of excitement

00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:28.126
around video recording, from
the very smallest developers

00:07:28.126 --> 00:07:29.750
to the largest we
have in the platform.

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:32.470
And more than a dozen
partners, including Netmarble,

00:07:32.470 --> 00:07:35.750
prominently, have already
launched an integration,

00:07:35.750 --> 00:07:38.824
because they are participating
in our early access program.

00:07:38.824 --> 00:07:40.990
And like I said, this will
be available to everybody

00:07:40.990 --> 00:07:41.905
in the coming weeks.

00:07:41.905 --> 00:07:43.780
And all the games that
you're seeing up here,

00:07:43.780 --> 00:07:45.790
you can check out on
the Play Store today,

00:07:45.790 --> 00:07:50.240
so you can get an idea of
how the integrations work.

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:53.680
One such excellent
integration is from a partner

00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:55.459
of ours, Camex Games.

00:07:55.459 --> 00:07:58.000
And I was really impressed for
a number of different reasons,

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.240
and I'll walk you through
how their integration works.

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:03.320
So from one of the
battle screens here,

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:06.580
you can see on
your left, there's

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:08.140
a little recording icon.

00:08:08.140 --> 00:08:12.020
And if you click that button,
it brings up a video recording

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:12.530
overlay.

00:08:12.530 --> 00:08:15.280
And from that overlay,
you have all the controls

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:17.550
you need to mute
the mic, turn on

00:08:17.550 --> 00:08:20.030
and off the
forward-facing camera,

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:25.650
as well as start and stop video
recording, as you would expect.

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:28.680
And then, once you're
done recording your video,

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:30.780
you can then share
it on YouTube.

00:08:30.780 --> 00:08:33.740
And you can see on the
screen on your right,

00:08:33.740 --> 00:08:37.190
here, that I've been able to
clip the video from the end.

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:39.350
And you can also observe
from the screenshot,

00:08:39.350 --> 00:08:45.630
here, that the engine
has prefilled the title

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:48.700
and description
with helpful data

00:08:48.700 --> 00:08:51.920
to speed up the process
of sharing replays.

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:58.100
And from Michael Tseng,
the COO of Camex Games,

00:08:58.100 --> 00:08:59.770
they said, "the
Google standalone

00:08:59.770 --> 00:09:02.610
Recording SDK took less
than a day to implement,

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:05.720
and players are recording
clips every day now."

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:07.340
Less than a day to implement.

00:09:07.340 --> 00:09:09.680
So it's a very quick
and easy integration.

00:09:09.680 --> 00:09:12.290
You can do it in a very
short period of time,

00:09:12.290 --> 00:09:14.720
and immediately get
your players engaged

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:17.640
with the video
recording capabilities.

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:19.620
And another thing
that I very much

00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:22.240
liked about their
integration was

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:26.257
that they made the feature
prominent in multiple places

00:09:26.257 --> 00:09:26.840
in their game.

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:29.920
So off of the main screen, you
could launch the recording--

00:09:29.920 --> 00:09:32.820
so ultimately, you could
share a much broader range

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:35.920
of experiences-- and they also
included, as I showed before,

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:37.150
from the battle screen.

00:09:37.150 --> 00:09:40.420
And the more visible the
feature is, the more likely

00:09:40.420 --> 00:09:44.146
your players are to
find it and use it.

00:09:44.146 --> 00:09:46.520
In addition to that, they also
turned the video recording

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:49.120
capabilities into a selling
point for Hero Tactics.

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:50.870
So when you go
into the game, they

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:52.970
would promote the
use of the feature,

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:55.079
and they even featured it
in their store listings.

00:09:55.079 --> 00:09:56.870
And all these different
things that they've

00:09:56.870 --> 00:10:00.120
done to provide visibility to
the video recording feature

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:01.700
have been very successful.

00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:06.110
So 12% of their users
have recorded videos,

00:10:06.110 --> 00:10:08.790
and most of them have
recorded multiple videos.

00:10:08.790 --> 00:10:10.780
And they share these
replays through all

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:14.370
the typical social channels,
as well as, very prominently,

00:10:14.370 --> 00:10:15.210
YouTube.

00:10:15.210 --> 00:10:19.680
It's a great way to engage
your audience deeply and have

00:10:19.680 --> 00:10:21.770
them sell your game for you.

00:10:21.770 --> 00:10:23.660
Very powerful stuff.

00:10:23.660 --> 00:10:26.830
So now I want to talk about how
Play Games can help you make

00:10:26.830 --> 00:10:29.990
dynamic updates to your game.

00:10:29.990 --> 00:10:33.780
And most developers that we
talk to, very successful ones,

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:35.240
manage their game as a service.

00:10:35.240 --> 00:10:38.450
And critical to that is being
able to dynamically control

00:10:38.450 --> 00:10:41.390
different aspects of their
game from the servers.

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:44.094
But it's a lot of hard
work to set up and manage

00:10:44.094 --> 00:10:45.760
these types of things,
and if you're not

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:48.720
a huge studio with
dedicated server engineers,

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:52.710
every minute you spend on this
kind of backend server work

00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:56.190
comes at the direct expense
of working on your game.

00:10:56.190 --> 00:11:00.800
Well, that's no
longer a requirement.

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:05.410
In the coming weeks, we'll be
able to use the Play Games Game

00:11:05.410 --> 00:11:09.560
Parameters Management Tool
so that you can dynamically

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:14.410
manage the different parameters
that drive your game.

00:11:14.410 --> 00:11:16.040
And with Game
Parameters Management,

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:18.290
you'll be able to manage
things like your virtual good

00:11:18.290 --> 00:11:21.040
inventory, your
gameplay parameters,

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:23.290
manage your
different currencies,

00:11:23.290 --> 00:11:26.800
and create time and
location-based overrides.

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:30.520
Now, the time and location-based
overrides are really useful.

00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:32.830
Many developers that offer
time-limited content,

00:11:32.830 --> 00:11:35.840
like a new character or
a level, and so forth,

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:40.140
still have to manually turn
on and off these promotions

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:41.290
and live events.

00:11:41.290 --> 00:11:46.411
So if your promotion, let's say,
ended at 11:59:59 on a Sunday,

00:11:46.411 --> 00:11:47.910
we've heard many
developers actually

00:11:47.910 --> 00:11:50.780
have to have someone
come into the office

00:11:50.780 --> 00:11:55.784
and hit a button to turn
off their promotion.

00:11:55.784 --> 00:11:57.450
There has to be a
better way to do this.

00:11:57.450 --> 00:12:01.860
And in fact, there is, and it
is Game Parameters Management,

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:02.910
just to be clear.

00:12:02.910 --> 00:12:04.720
So if you are running
a global business

00:12:04.720 --> 00:12:08.670
and you want promotions to be
run at locally-relevant times,

00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:10.420
with our time and
country-based overrides,

00:12:10.420 --> 00:12:14.230
you'll be able to specify
country-specific start and stop

00:12:14.230 --> 00:12:19.232
times, and we automatically
manage everything for you.

00:12:19.232 --> 00:12:20.690
And like all of
our other features,

00:12:20.690 --> 00:12:23.975
this will be available for
free in the Developer console.

00:12:26.860 --> 00:12:28.880
And we've been
working very closely

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:30.970
with our partner,
